world. Contemporary theories of perception disagree about the role of content and conceptual capacities in perceptual experience. In her analysis El Kassar scrutinizes the arguments of conceptualist and relationist theories, thereby exposing their limitations for explaining the epistemic role of perceptual experience. Against this background she develops her novel theory of epistemically significant perception. Her theory improves on current accounts by encompassing both the epistemic role of perceptual experiences and its perceptual character. Central claims of her theory receive additional support from work in vision science, making this book an original contribution to the philosophy of perception.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aConceptualism. 0aPerception (Philosophy). 0aRelationism. 4aKonzeptualismus. 4aMcDowell, John. 4aRelationismus. 4aWahrnehmung. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Epistemology.2bisacsh  aConceptualism.  aperception.  arelationism.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus DeG Package 2015 Part 1z978311076251808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus eBook-Package 2015z978311070098508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2015z9783110439687oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Philosophy 2015z9783110438680oZDB-23-DPH0 cEPUBz97831104453670 cprintz978311044521340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978311044562640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783110445626423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9783110445626/original  a978-3-11-070098-5  DG Plus eBook-Package 2015b2015  a978-3-11-076251-8  DG Plus DeG Package 2015 Part 1b2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_DGALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL